@lbfalvy You can think of `fn` items as syntactic sugar for of a struct and some impls. For example `fn example(arg1: u32, arg2: bool) -> String {…}` becomes:

```rust
struct example;

impl FnOnce<(u32, bool)> for example {
    type Output = String;

    extern "rust-call" fn call_once(self, args: (u32, bool)) -> String {…}
}
```

Now if the function itself is generic like `fn channel<T>() -> (Sender<T>, Receiver<T>) {…}`, the equivalent expansion would have that `T` be a parameter of the *struct*. Then the impl can reference it without any problem when defining the associated type:


```rust
struct channel<T>(PhantomData<T>);

impl<T> FnOnce<()> for channel<T> {
    type Output = (Sender<T>, Receiver<T>);

    extern "rust-call" fn call_once(self, args: ()) -> (Sender<T>, Receiver<T>) {…}
}
```

@lbfalvy For closures that return a reference, the lifetime bound must be a generic parameter (or `'static`). Otherwise the compiler does not know how the lifetimes of the output relates to the passed in arguments. This is solved by letting the closure implement the Fn-trait for every possible lifetime. If Args were an associated type, it would be impossible to specify this relation between argument and output lifetimes. For example, the following would be impossible to write/compile:
```rust
fn example(closure_with_lifetime: impl for<'a> Fn(&'a mut [i32]) -> &'a mut i32) {
    let mut x = [1,2,3];
    *closure_with_lifetime(&mut x) = 4;
    println!("{:?}", x);
}

fn main() {
    example(|list| &mut list[0]); // Outputs: [4, 2, 3]
    example(|list| &mut list[2]); // Outputs: [1, 2, 4]
}
```

Furthermore accessing the argument types of a closure is already possible in stable rust through some newtype and trait magic. See: https://play.rust-lang.org/?version=stable&mode=debug&edition=2024&gist=87f1640346ae159008a40c6e1e2cc894. It obviously does not work with higher trait bounds such as in the example above, as that requires the lifetime to be a generic parameter.

It looks better to me to change to

```rust
type Output;
fn ()(self, args);
```

Perhaps this would work well with future variable parameters
